liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: President Joe Biden swept into wartime Israel for a 7.5-hour visit that produced a heaping dose of vocal support, a deal to get limited humanitarian aid into Gaza from Egypt and a plea for Israelis not to allow rage over the deadly Hamas attack to consume them. "I understand. Many Americans understand," Mr Biden said as he wrapped up his stay in Tel Aviv, He likened the October 7 Hamas attack to the 9/11 terrorist attack in the US that killed nearly 3,000 people in 2001. "You can't look at what has happened here … and not scream out for justice," he said. "But I caution this: While you feel that rage, don't be consumed by it," he said. "After 9/11, we were enraged in the United States. And while we sought justice and got justice, we also made mistakes." He urged Israel to step back from the brink, not just to ease growing tensions in the middle east that threaten to spiral into a broader regional conflict, but also to reassure a world rattled by images of carnage and suffering, in Israel and Gaza alike. Aboard the flight back to Washington Biden spoke by phone with Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi who agreed to reopen his country’s sealed border crossing with Gaza and allow up to 20 trucks carrying humanitarian aid supplies to cross. Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, Biden said roads near the crossing would first need hours of repairs, but that aid could begin rolling into the region by Friday. AP/ABC
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Biden wraps up 7.5 hour Israel visit with warning against being 'consumed' by rage

children.content: President Joe Biden swept into wartime Israel for a 7.5-hour visit that produced a heaping dose of vocal support, a deal to get limited humanitarian aid into Gaza from Egypt and a plea for Israelis not to allow rage over the deadly Hamas attack to consume them.
"I understand. Many Americans understand," Mr Biden said as he wrapped up his stay in Tel Aviv,
He likened the October 7 Hamas attack to the 9/11 terrorist attack in the US that killed nearly 3,000 people in 2001.
"You can't look at what has happened here … and not scream out for justice," he said.

"But I caution this: While you feel that rage, don't be consumed by it," he said. "After 9/11, we were enraged in the United States. And while we sought justice and got justice, we also made mistakes."

props.alt: An image of Biden wearing a blue zip up fleece while saluting.

children.content: Joe Biden has landed in the US at the Join Base Andrews in Maryland.
(Reuters: Evelyn Hockstein)

He urged Israel to step back from the brink, not just to ease growing tensions in the middle east that threaten to spiral into a broader regional conflict, but also to reassure a world rattled by images of carnage and suffering, in Israel and Gaza alike.

Aboard the flight back to Washington Biden spoke by phone with Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi who agreed to reopen his country’s sealed border crossing with Gaza and allow up to 20 trucks carrying humanitarian aid supplies to cross.
Speaking to reporters aboard Air Force One, Biden said roads near the crossing would first need hours of repairs, but that aid could begin rolling into the region by Friday.
AP/ABC

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: By political reporter Tom Lowrey The Opposition leader has called on the Prime Minister to visit Israel, as part of a trip to the United States next week. Anthony Albanese is expected to depart for Washington DC early next week, where he will be hosted by President Joe Biden at a state dinner. At the end of Question Time, Peter Dutton told federal parliament Mr Albanese should be visiting Israel's leadership in Tel Aviv too, as a show of support in the ongoing Israel-Gaza war. He said it should take precedence above any other commitments. "It would be in our country's best interest to go via Tel Aviv, and provide support to the Israeli leadership," he said. "It is important for us to be able to stand with Israel at this time, as other world leaders have done. "That should be the priority of any international travel at the moment, as we seek to be part of an alliance to keep the pressure down on those who seek to have a wider conflict in the region." President Biden visited Israel overnight, closely following a visit from German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, while UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak will visit soon.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Peter Dutton calls on Anthony Albanese to visit Israel as part of US trip next week

He said it should take precedence above any other commitments.
"It would be in our country's best interest to go via Tel Aviv, and provide support to the Israeli leadership," he said.
"It is important for us to be able to stand with Israel at this time, as other world leaders have done.
"That should be the priority of any international travel at the moment, as we seek to be part of an alliance to keep the pressure down on those who seek to have a wider conflict in the region."
President Biden visited Israel overnight, closely following a visit from German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, while UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak will visit soon.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: With hundreds reported dead, many more injured and growing international outrage, the explosion at al-Ahli Arab hospital in Gaza demands examination and accountability. But there are many reasons why people are not sure who to blame. Uncertainty about who was responsible for the blast arose in part because Gazans have argued that many sites, such as mosques, schools and ambulances — even the crossing out of Gaza into Egypt — have been struck by Israel in this conflict. Israel said such sites host fighters, arms or equipment and that groups like Hamas use civilian infrastructure. Here's what we know about the competing narratives and key evidence surrounding the incident:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Dairy cooperative Norco was ravaged by floods at the start of last year, and its ice cream factory went under. But not only is it back in profit — making $9.1 million — it's also making ice cream again! Talk about some much-needed good news after the past week or so (especially with summer on our doorstep). From my colleague Kim Honan, the report says: Norco has      delivered its second-highest profit to farmer members The dairy      cooperative paid its suppliers a record milk price for the year Its ice      cream factory is due to start operating after a major rebuild      following the 2022 floods Read more, and see just how far under the factory was in the devastating flood, in this report — link below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: With an hour of trading left today, the ASX is continuing to follow Wall Street into negative territory, down 1.6% as of 3pm AEDT to 6,962 points. (If you want live figures, head to the top of the blog.) All 11 major sectors are in negative territory, with academic and educational services seeing the biggest fall — it's shed 3.9%. The second-biggest drop has hit industrials (-2%) followed by financials (-1.9%), real estate (-1.8%) and consumer non-cyclicals (-1.7%). Basic materials and consumer cyclicals are down 1.6% each, while technology stocks are down 1.3%, followed by healthcare (-1.2%) and energy (1.2%). Utilities has had the smallest fall so far today, down just 0.3%. The top performers this afternoon: Weebit Nano +7.4% Northern Star Resources +3.9% ARB Corporation +3.4% Bapcor +1.8% Hub24 +1.4% And the worst performing stocks: Telix Pharmaceuticals -10.9% Netwealth Group -8.2% Chalice Mining -7.4% Allkem -6.3% Pilbara Minerals -6.3%
